<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=101654384968572></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101654384968572><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101654384968572>RE: tell yet another befuddles newbie!!</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=8&mid=101654384968572#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=151942><span id=Guru>Kelanthor</span></a>, <span id=Guru>Guru</span><br><span id=notbold>108 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Mar 19th 8:20 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I'm not that far ahead of you in the experience stakes, but I hunted exclusively in GFay on my way up, and have a few pointers for you.<br><br>Abbreviations: DD - Direct Damage (Burst of Flame, Burst of Fire, Invoke Lightning, Ward Summoned, Whirling Wind)<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;             DoT - Damage over Time (Flame Lick)<br>               Buff - Statistic/Armor Class/Hit point booster.<br><br>Spells: Your lvl 9 spells will cost a fair bit each (check the exact costs out in the Guild) so make sure and save enough to buy them. You might want to purchase your buffs first (Firefist, Thistlecoat, Strength of Earth) followed by your new DD spell (Ignite) and Light Healing. Shield of Thistles is OK, but doesn't deal out much damage or last very long at 9th level. Purchase the rest in whichever order you find them most useful.<br><br>Tactics: With the spells you have before 9th level, you can either Snare/Flame Lick/melee (if your armour and weapons are up to it) or Grasping Roots/Flame Lick/Burst of Fire. Try and do a little melee, as it is the only way to get your weapon and offense skills moving. You can get better at spell-casting by just repeatedly casting a spell of the type you wish to improve. You'll find Evoke goes up quickly in battle, but others are more problematic. Use Dance of The Fireflies and Whirling Wind to improve your Conjuring skill. (Important as Lvl 14 DoT spell is Conjuration, NOT Evocation). Keep as many buffs as possible active on yourself, and watch that Abjure skill rise! Using Camouflage to get yourself into position without being attacked will also help your Divination skill. Remember to put just one point into Meditate when your reach 8th level - you'll never need another! Every time you want to recover mana after that, instead of just sitting, open your spellbook and watch that skill race up to max. Note that maximum for any non-trade skill is (5 x level)+ 5. You can't see the numeric value of skills below 100, so keep an eye out in your chat window for the numbers when they do increase.<br><br>Money: I'm still poor, but am gradually managing to get some platinum together, as well as a few pieces of decent equipment. Look out for folk auctioning stuff near the bank in Kelethin and go have a look. Make them an offer, you might be surprised what you can pick up. Also, I've had decent low-level stuff given to me by higher level folk who have no use for it (Shiny Brass Shield, Flint Hammer). Look out for folk wanting stacks of silk and wings - or better still, put a point or two into Tailoring and start making your own bandages (which sell for not too bad a profit). Go through into Butcherblock and hunt the large spiders for their silk (which makes swatches) and sell stacks of those to master tailors. If you do decide to tailor yourself, head for East Commons, as Semimaster suggests - lots of spiders, bears, pumas and lions there for supplies! Look for orcs with staves in GFay - most of the time, these are of the 'worn great' type, but I've picked up quite a few 'cracked' ones, which go for 1pp 3gp to merchants in Kelethin. One of the best money-makers (although it depends a lot on luck) is Morning Dew, from your Forage skill. This is in big demand for making Wood Elf racial armour, and individual sacks go for 3-5pp. I've had a couple of players offer 70pp if I can put a stack together, but it's so rare, I think you're better off selling it individually at low levels. Crushbone belts are a good 2-sided item. You can either run over to Kaladim  with a load and turn them into Canloe (Warriors Guild) for experience, or sell bags of them to other players for at least 1pp per belt. Pads go at an even bigger price.<br><br>Hope this lot helps - it's not a definitive guide, but I've muddled through pretty well (and with no deaths since 6th level) with it. One final tip - try and get in a group, as your experience and money will rise a lot quicker. You have to balance that with keeping your skills up to the level you've attained, however, or you'll have problems in later life.<br><br>Good hunting!<br>&nbsp;<br>Kelanthor<br>Wood Elf Druid of the 41st Circle<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=212672</a></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

